01:09:36.390 --> 01:09:39.189
We have a big engineering
controversy constantly going

01:09:39.189 --> 01:09:42.770
on about the economy of scale
and bigger and bigger plants.

01:09:42.770 --> 01:09:47.569
But the bigger plants sometimes
bring new problems to bear.

01:09:47.569 --> 01:09:50.149
So if you give up
economy of scale,

01:09:50.149 --> 01:09:52.510
you also get, in
return, the economy

01:09:52.510 --> 01:09:54.270
of the learning
curve, because you're

01:09:54.270 --> 01:09:56.070
going to produce more units.

01:09:56.070 --> 01:09:59.400
So I think the smaller
units are going to win out.

01:10:03.330 --> 01:10:04.210
Go ahead.

01:10:04.210 --> 01:10:04.890
AUDIENCE: Me?

01:10:04.890 --> 01:10:06.015
DR. ROBERT HARGRAVES: Sure.

01:10:06.015 --> 01:10:08.330
AUDIENCE: Yeah, Bob, a
question on your chart showing

01:10:08.330 --> 01:10:11.090
the kilowatt cost
per kilowatt hour

01:10:11.090 --> 01:10:13.710
of the various alternative.

01:10:13.710 --> 01:10:17.060
Is there any attempt to
include the transmission costs?

01:10:17.060 --> 01:10:19.870
Or are transmission
costs not relevant?

01:10:19.870 --> 01:10:23.150
DR. ROBERT HARGRAVES: I did
not include transmission costs.

01:10:23.150 --> 01:10:26.060
They can make a
difference, if you

01:10:26.060 --> 01:10:28.650
are thinking about powering
the US with renewables

01:10:28.650 --> 01:10:32.710
from long-distance power
sources-- something like,

01:10:32.710 --> 01:10:35.150
figure a penny per kilowatt
hour per 1,000 miles

01:10:35.150 --> 01:10:37.082
of high-voltage DC transmission.

01:10:37.082 --> 01:10:38.790
Keep that number in
the back of your mind

01:10:38.790 --> 01:10:40.539
when you're trying to
design these things.

01:10:43.415 --> 01:10:44.956
Please.

01:10:44.956 --> 01:10:46.644
AUDIENCE: Right.

01:10:46.644 --> 01:10:50.620
Is the nuclear waste
produced by these plants

01:10:50.620 --> 01:10:53.883
different in some sense than
waste produced by light water

01:10:53.883 --> 01:10:55.034
reactors?

01:10:55.034 --> 01:10:57.200
DR. ROBERT HARGRAVES: Is
the nuclear waste different

01:10:57.200 --> 01:10:59.440
than the waste produced
by light water reactors?

01:10:59.440 --> 01:11:01.120
Yeah, it's quite different.

01:11:01.120 --> 01:11:03.660
The light water
reactors' waste is

01:11:03.660 --> 01:11:05.770
in the same fuel
form it went in,

01:11:05.770 --> 01:11:10.130
so fuel rods that are
then to be disposed

01:11:10.130 --> 01:11:13.950
of at some future,
undetermined place.

01:11:13.950 --> 01:11:19.640
The molten salt reactor can
continue to operate and consume

01:11:19.640 --> 01:11:24.930
a lot of the sort of
actinides-- the heavy uranium--

01:11:24.930 --> 01:11:28.970
the heavy elements, like
plutonium, americium,

01:11:28.970 --> 01:11:31.570
californium, well, and so on.

01:11:31.570 --> 01:11:37.130
So the long-lived heavy
metal, radioactive products

01:11:37.130 --> 01:11:39.860
continue to be consumed.

01:11:39.860 --> 01:11:41.620
Now, when you finally
stop the reactor,

01:11:41.620 --> 01:11:43.410
you're going to have
some of those left.

01:11:43.410 --> 01:11:47.110
So the amount of that
waste per kilowatt hour

01:11:47.110 --> 01:11:48.500
that was generated is lower.

01:11:48.500 --> 01:11:50.830
But you're still going to
have that kind of waste

01:11:50.830 --> 01:11:52.720
to deal with at some point.

01:11:52.720 --> 01:11:54.860
In addition, both
kinds of reactors

01:11:54.860 --> 01:11:59.130
generate the fission products--
that is, the cesium or iodine

01:11:59.130 --> 01:12:03.570
or whatever it is, xenon,
strothium, and so on,

01:12:03.570 --> 01:12:05.810
that you've heard of--
which come from splitting

01:12:05.810 --> 01:12:10.470
those big, heavy nuclei
of uranium and plutonium.

01:12:10.470 --> 01:12:12.500
Both kind of reactors
generate the same kind

01:12:12.500 --> 01:12:13.820
of fission products.

01:12:13.820 --> 01:12:17.910
But the decay time for those is
on the order of a few hundred

01:12:17.910 --> 01:12:22.840
years before they're really more
or less benign for handling.

01:12:22.840 --> 01:12:27.320
So the answer is, there's less
of the waste per kilowatt hour

01:12:27.320 --> 01:12:31.860
generated-- less of a long-life
waste per kilowatt hour

01:12:31.860 --> 01:12:34.380
generated, about the
same amount of waste

01:12:34.380 --> 01:12:37.060
per kilowatt hour generated
for the fission products that

01:12:37.060 --> 01:12:38.295
have the shorter lifetimes.

01:12:41.090 --> 01:12:43.873
AUDIENCE: So, if we were to,
say, try and replace as much

01:12:43.873 --> 01:12:47.450
of the coal and natural
gas power infrastructure

01:12:47.450 --> 01:12:50.760
with liquid thorium
reactors instead,

01:12:50.760 --> 01:12:53.310
how much would we
still need in the mix

01:12:53.310 --> 01:12:56.224
to provide peak and
on-demand power?

01:12:56.224 --> 01:12:58.390
Because I'm assuming even
the smaller thorium plants

01:12:58.390 --> 01:13:02.224
won't be able to come up on
demand to respond to the grid.

01:13:02.224 --> 01:13:03.890
DR. ROBERT HARGRAVES:
Yeah, the question

01:13:03.890 --> 01:13:06.370
is, would you need some kind
of peaking plants in addition

01:13:06.370 --> 01:13:08.078
to the nuclear power
plants, because they

01:13:08.078 --> 01:13:10.950
are slow to respond
to demand changes?

01:13:10.950 --> 01:13:12.444
Well, the current
plants are slow,

01:13:12.444 --> 01:13:14.360
basically because they
were designed that way.

01:13:14.360 --> 01:13:17.050
And they could have been
designed to be more responsive.

01:13:17.050 --> 01:13:19.320
But they haven't.

01:13:19.320 --> 01:13:23.860
They are designed to recover
all their costs at full power.

01:13:23.860 --> 01:13:28.410
So the owners of those plants
don't want to turn them down.

01:13:28.410 --> 01:13:30.630
Now, the newer plants
will have the same issue,

01:13:30.630 --> 01:13:36.660
in the sense of, can we-- do
we want to turn them down?

01:13:36.660 --> 01:13:39.120
The owners will say, no, I
want to keep generating money.

01:13:39.120 --> 01:13:41.370
So that's the real issue.

01:13:41.370 --> 01:13:44.435
You can engineer it to make
it go-- turn it down pretty

01:13:44.435 --> 01:13:45.120
easily.

01:13:45.120 --> 01:13:47.834
The plants do what's
called load following.

01:13:47.834 --> 01:13:50.000
That is, if you diminish
the load on the power plant

01:13:50.000 --> 01:13:55.260
by turning off the lights
or breaking a pylon

01:13:55.260 --> 01:13:58.910
and ruining the
load on the plant,

01:13:58.910 --> 01:14:01.560
the ability to dissipate
heat disappears.

01:14:01.560 --> 01:14:03.650
The temperature of
the reactor goes up.

01:14:03.650 --> 01:14:06.320
And the physics of
the reactor designs

01:14:06.320 --> 01:14:08.570
shuts it down, or slows it down.

01:14:08.570 --> 01:14:10.520
That same principle
means it automatically

01:14:10.520 --> 01:14:12.020
does load following.

01:14:12.020 --> 01:14:17.910
So you can indeed have these
plants run at a lower speed

01:14:17.910 --> 01:14:22.302
and not require backup
from, say, natural gas,

01:14:22.302 --> 01:14:23.260
or something like that.

01:14:29.030 --> 01:14:31.050
Thank you.

